```cs
// File1.cs
namespace App.Widget
{
    class Inner { }
}

// File2.cs
namespace App
{
    file class Widget { } // unexpected error: The namespace 'App' already contains a definition for 'Widget' in this file.
}
```

Per [specification](https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/blob/main/proposals/csharp-11.0/file-local-types.md#lookup), we should not get an error here, and usages of `App.Widget` in `File2.cs` should refer to `file class App.Widget`, not to `namespace App.Widget`.

> ### Lookup
> We amend the [member lookup](https://github.com/dotnet/csharpstandard/blob/draft-v7/standard/expressions.md#115-member-lookup) section as follows (new text in **bold**):
> 
> > - Next, if `K` is zero, all nested types whose declarations include type parameters are removed. If `K` is not zero, all members with a different number of type parameters are removed. When `K` is zero, methods having type parameters are not removed, since the type inference process ([§11.6.3](https://github.com/dotnet/csharpstandard/blob/draft-v7/standard/expressions.md#1163-type-inference)) might be able to infer the type arguments.
> > - **Next, let *F* be the compilation unit which contains the expression where member lookup is occurring. All members which are file-local types and are not declared in *F* are removed from the set.**
> > - **Next, if the set of accessible members contains file-local types, all non-file-local types are removed from the set.**

When a method has multiple lambda functions which capture variables, all variables are captured together in a single 'DisplayClass'. This means that ALL of the variables will remain alive as long as ANY of the lambdas are still alive. This is discussed here: https://www.jetbrains.com/help/resharper/ImplicitlyCapturedClosure.html

This is a problem if some of those variables are holding onto lots of memory and the lifetime of some of the lambdas is long. This is frequently an issue where a method processes some data using Linq, then sets up subscriptions to events using lambdas (such as through System.Reactive), in the same method. 

## Proposal

Allow an attribute `NarrowCapture` to be attached to a lambda which instructs the compiler to create a separate DisplayClass for that lambda, and box any variables that are shared with other lambdas. Additionally allow attributes to be placed on the Action/Func parameters of a method, and follow these so the attribute does not need to be defined with every usage.

**Pros** - Gives developers a tool to control the lifetime of their variables without needing to create separate methods. Massive potential savings on memory leaks.
**Cons** - Performance / memory hit due to additional boxing and extra classes. Somewhat larger assembly size.

## Example
``` C#

// Tells the compiler to create a separate DisplayClass if on a lambda or a method parameter
public class NarrowCaptureAttribute : Attribute { }

public class MyForm : Form
{
    public MyForm()
    {
        var caption = "Hello";

        //Lots of memory which currently is held for the life of ALL lambdas
        var arr = new double[100_000_000]; 

        //Lambda 1, marked NarrowCapture, captures arr, caption
        var sum = Enumerable.Range(0, arr.Length).Sum([NarrowCapture](i) => arr[i] + caption.Length); 

        //Lambda 2, captures caption, sum
        Shown += (sender, args) => Text = $"{caption} :: {sum}"; 

        //Lambda 3, captures caption
        SizeChanged += (sender, args) => Text = $"{caption} Size Changed"; 
    }

    //For the method in general - will be alive until all related lambdas are dead
    private class MockDisplayClass 
    {
        //This is boxed because it's used in the [NarrowCapture] lambda so it can be shared
        public StrongBox<string> caption; 

        public double sum;

        //This does not need arr - because it's not used in the remaining two lambdas not marked with [NarrowCapture]
    }

    //For Lambda 1 - will die with Lambda 1
    private class NarrowMockDisplayClass1
    {
        public double[] arr;
        public StrongBox<string> caption;
    }
}

//Example where a method parameter has [NarrowCapture], so any lambdas used *directly* would get this applied.
static double Sum<T>(T[] arr, [NarrowCapture] Func<T, double> selector)
{
    return arr.Sum(selector);
}
```

I'm not fully aware of how the compiler works - please excuse me if this is way off the mark for how C# works.

